<body>

<div>
<h2>Today lets look at two things that are almost the same in CSS. (but not really)</h2>
  <p>Both define a group of styles that can be selected to be applied together to an element.</p>
</div>
  

<div class="aClass">
  <h1>A CSS Class</h1>
<ul>
  <li> Used where the style group must be applied to multiple elements</li>
  <li> Defined with .</li>
  <li> Called with class="xxxx"</li>  
  </ul>
</div>



<div class="anId">
<h1>A CSS ID</h1>
<ul>
  <li> Used to target one particular element with the style group</li>
  <li> Defined with #</li>
  <li> id="xxxx"</li>  
  </ul>
  
  </div>
  </body>
  
  
  
  
  
  
  
body{
  background-color:#BFD3C1;
  color: #694F5D;
  
  font-family:Sans-Serif;
}
.aClass{
  position:absolute;
  margin:0px 20px 20px 200px;
  left:0;
  width: 400px;  
   background-color: #68A691;
  font-size: 130%;
 
}
h1{
  text-align:center;
}
.anId{
  position:absolute;
  margin:0px 200px 20px 20px;
  right:0;
  width: 400px;
  background-color: #68A691;
  font-size: 130%;
 
  
}
 h2{
  text-align: center;
  font-size: 220%;
  
  
  
}

p{
    text-align: center;

}
div{
  padding: 9px;
  margin: 20px;
  border: 2px solid grey;
  background-color: #B2b6AB;

 
}
